<div id="review_1123864174" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1123864174" />
    <a title="Kendall" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1578804-kendall"><img alt="Kendall" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1226240703p2/1578804.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1123864174?book_show_action=true">Dec 05, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kendall" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kendall" href="/user/show/1578804-kendall">Kendall</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781400040490" href="/book/show/282434.The_Complete_Short_Novels">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1123864174" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16788927574067850055">The thing I like about Chekhov is the fact his writing is so accessible. That is, the language, the words, the sentences do not read as if they were written over 100 years ago. Reading his work isn’t laborious, it’s as engaging and seamless as any contemporary work of fiction. And his interpretations of human nature and behavior are just as relevant today as they were back then.<br/><br/>I don’t know how much of Chekhov’s accessibility in this case is due to Richard Pevear and Larissa Volokhonsky’s transl</span>
  <span id="freeText16788927574067850055" style="display:none">The thing I like about Chekhov is the fact his writing is so accessible. That is, the language, the words, the sentences do not read as if they were written over 100 years ago. Reading his work isn’t laborious, it’s as engaging and seamless as any contemporary work of fiction. And his interpretations of human nature and behavior are just as relevant today as they were back then.<br /><br />I don’t know how much of Chekhov’s accessibility in this case is due to Richard Pevear and Larissa Volokhonsky’s translation of his work, but if you’re looking for a good place to start with Chekhov, I think this is it.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16788927574067850055" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


